    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, it is absolutely possible to have unexpected memory spikes even when using generators, and this often points toward something outside the generator itself. A common culprit is holding onto references to large objects *outside* the generator's immediate scope, or perhaps an operation *inside* the loop that isn't properly releasing memory. Sometimes, if you're processing the data and then storing intermediate results in a standard Python list *inside* the loop, you'll negate the memory-saving benefit of the generator.\n\nYou might also be running into issues with Pandas itself if you're reading chunks and then performing operations that create new, large copies of the data structure. The best practice is to ensure that any variables holding the data chunk are explicitly deleted or fall out of scope immediately after they are processed. If the memory usage seems erratic, it's a good sign to profile your code to see exactly which lines are causing the allocation spikes.",
      "source": "target",
