      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That subtle, constant \"snatching\" of memory, even after diligent cleanup, often suggests issues related to object caching or, more commonly in C-backed libraries like Pandas, internal memory management that isn't perfectly garbage-collected in the way you expect. It's less likely a pure Python bug and more often related to how underlying C libraries manage their buffers.\n\nOne potential culprit is **reference cycles** if you are creating complex object relationships, though this usually causes a larger eventual spike rather than a constant drip. Another possibility, especially when dealing with I/O or large data structures, is that the garbage collector isn't being triggered frequently enough, letting temporary allocations linger. If the problem persists, consider explicitly calling `gc.collect()` periodically within your loop to force the Python garbage collector to run and reclaim any temporary memory immediately.",
      "source": "target",
